00:00:02.800 --> 00:00:07.480
we released RStudio Connect 1.9 with new features

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:11.400
for content curation to build your ideal showcase of data

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:12.880
products.

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:15.000
And so today, Kelly is going to go

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:17.600
through a demo of the new functionality.

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:20.559
And we'll be here to answer any and all questions

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:21.959
that you have.

00:00:21.959 --> 00:00:24.440
So again, please feel free to use the chat window

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:26.000
to ask questions.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.160
Or I'll put the Slido link in there shortly

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:31.120
if there's anything you want to ask anonymously as well.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.720
And with that, I will turn it over to you, Kelly.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:41.360
Awesome.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:42.439
Thanks, Rachel.

00:00:42.439 --> 00:00:44.520
I'm going to share my screen here.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:51.639
All right.

00:00:51.639 --> 00:00:55.959
Hopefully that's showing up OK for you.

00:00:55.959 --> 00:00:56.480
Yep.

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:57.119
I can see it.

00:00:57.119 --> 00:00:59.040
It's not in the presentation mode yet,

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:01.480
but I can see the slide.

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:05.000
I'm going to be hopping through the browser

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:07.720
and in and out of my RStudio IDE.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:09.839
So I'm just going to keep it like this.

00:01:09.839 --> 00:01:11.919
It doesn't bother everybody.

00:01:11.919 --> 00:01:12.639
No, that's good.

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:13.919
I'm going to present like this.

00:01:13.919 --> 00:01:15.440
It gives a casual feel.

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:19.599
So feel free to ask as many questions as you want.

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:23.040
I also want to give a call out to Katie Maciela, who's

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:26.239
on the call as well, who's one of our CS reps.

00:01:26.239 --> 00:01:29.120
She took some slides that I built

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:30.639
and built some better slides.

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:33.320
And then I took her slides and turned them into these slides.

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:35.400
So Katie, thank you for your slides.

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:37.480
I will just keep passing them back and forth

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:39.839
and improving upon them forever.

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:42.879
And it will be great.

00:01:42.879 --> 00:01:44.919
Thank you for that.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:45.559
So welcome.

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:48.519
I'm here today to talk about RStudio Connect

00:01:48.519 --> 00:01:53.400
and the release we did last month, which was 1.9.0.

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:59.120
It introduces some new functionality and a new R

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:01.839
package called Connect Widgets.

00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:07.279
That is the big headline for this release and R package,

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:12.360
actually, not anything having to do with Connect code at all.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:14.279
There's a little bit of functionality

00:02:14.279 --> 00:02:15.360
that went along with that.

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:19.839
I'll talk about some quality of life improvements,

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:22.199
we'll call them, to go along with this package as part

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:24.039
of the 1.9.0 release.

00:02:24.039 --> 00:02:27.639
But largely, this is about an external R package

00:02:27.639 --> 00:02:30.520
we produced to add some functionality that I think

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:33.839
was really missing in the product itself.

00:02:33.839 --> 00:02:37.440
This is the Connect Widgets official HEX logo,

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:40.279
but we haven't officially made stickers of it yet.

00:02:40.279 --> 00:02:45.639
But Edgar Lees put together this HEX logo himself for us.

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:50.839
And so I wanted to give him a special call on his call.

00:02:50.880 --> 00:02:52.960
But in order to level set here, I

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:57.080
want to make sure that everybody is on the same page with us

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:00.440
as we talk about Connect and talk about the feature

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:05.360
set that Connect Widgets plugs into here.

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:12.240
When I think about Connect, I am thinking as a product manager

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:16.479
across a large number of different user profiles.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:20.800
So I think about what Connect can do for the admin.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:23.600
I think about what it can do for the data science leader,

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:26.600
what it can do for the stakeholders, the viewers.

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:30.440
But mostly, because of my background

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:32.919
in data science myself, I think about what Connect

00:03:32.919 --> 00:03:34.759
can do for the publisher.

00:03:34.759 --> 00:03:36.759
And when I think about the publisher actions that

00:03:36.759 --> 00:03:39.199
exist on Connect, I'm sort of thinking

00:03:39.199 --> 00:03:43.000
along four different vectors, thinking about what Connect

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:44.600
can do for deployment.

00:03:44.639 --> 00:03:48.440
That means deploying different artifacts in R and Python.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:51.279
And you can choose from a number of different deployment

00:03:51.279 --> 00:03:52.080
mechanisms.

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:54.199
You can go push button deployment.

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:57.839
You can deploy Python content through a CLI.

00:03:57.839 --> 00:04:02.720
You can plug into your Git version control system

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:05.000
and do Git back deployment.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.559
Or you could even fully customize,

00:04:09.559 --> 00:04:13.800
scope out deployment pipeline using our server API.

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:15.639
So you've got lots of different options

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:20.000
that take you from the basic, getting something off

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.480
of your laptop, capturing the basics of that environment,

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:27.079
and putting it on to a shared server,

00:04:27.079 --> 00:04:33.119
all the way to DevOps-style deployments, CICD.

00:04:33.119 --> 00:04:35.200
You think about execution.

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:38.480
You can choose between publishing static content

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:42.160
or publishing content that's backed by the source code

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:46.040
itself so that you can set it up to run on a schedule.

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:50.320
Or you can control the number of processes and connections

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:52.760
to that process if you have an interactive content type,

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:55.559
like an application or an API.

00:04:55.559 --> 00:04:56.679
I think about management.

00:04:56.679 --> 00:04:59.359
I want to control the metadata that

00:04:59.359 --> 00:05:02.880
is associated with this individual content item.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:06.359
I want to be able to publish new versions of it in place,

00:05:06.359 --> 00:05:08.679
like roll them forward, backward,

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:12.799
do blue-green-style deployments between different content

00:05:12.799 --> 00:05:13.839
items.

00:05:13.839 --> 00:05:16.799
I want to be able to access the report history

00:05:16.799 --> 00:05:19.839
if I have a scheduled report and see

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:24.239
the history of what I've been producing over time.

00:05:24.239 --> 00:05:28.399
And I want to be able to do some light organization with tags

00:05:28.399 --> 00:05:31.000
and track usage widgets.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.600
For the final step, distribution,

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:36.640
I'm thinking about actually making

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:38.359
an impact in my organization.

00:05:38.359 --> 00:05:40.359
How am I going to get this content

00:05:40.359 --> 00:05:44.200
that I've spent so much time deploying and crafting

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:49.000
and managing into the hands of people who actually need it?

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:50.880
Sometimes it's just you who needs something,

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:52.880
or it's you, your future self, who

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:55.000
needs to be able to find something.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.679
Sometimes it's a group of larger folks

00:05:57.679 --> 00:06:00.079
who you want to distribute this thing to.

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:03.760
You want this to be a showcase of what you're producing

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:05.480
for your organization for.

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:09.160
And so it's important to be able to make sure

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:11.079
they can find that thing on Connect,

00:06:11.079 --> 00:06:12.880
or make sure you've sent that out

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:14.920
and through the proper channels.

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:17.320
So you can distribute content that

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:20.480
was on Connect through custom emails.

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:23.760
You can set vanity URLs.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:25.359
There are a number of things that you

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:29.600
can do to distribute individual content items today.

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:34.920
And this makes for a really great, cool experience

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:37.160
for managing individual content items.

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:40.880
So I'll just go ahead and just, again,

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:42.600
so that we're level setting, make sure

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:45.959
that everybody knows what these features look like,

00:06:45.959 --> 00:06:50.399
at least from the management and distribution side.

00:06:50.399 --> 00:06:52.679
So I've produced this report.

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:55.880
It's based on this silly toy project

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:57.959
that I put together called Cookie Cutter Shop,

00:06:57.959 --> 00:07:00.320
where I was managing an Etsy shop

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:04.720
to sell cookie cutters in the shape of the R logo.

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:07.799
I was selling them in three different colors.

00:07:07.799 --> 00:07:09.679
They were purple, black, and red.

00:07:09.679 --> 00:07:13.000
And as people were ordering them off of the Etsy shop,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
my inventory was soaring.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.239
And then I would have to update those inventory levels

00:07:19.239 --> 00:07:22.399
and then start printing more on my 3D printer

00:07:22.399 --> 00:07:25.799
in each of those colors as the inventory burned down.

00:07:25.799 --> 00:07:29.480
So I was producing these inventory burned down charts

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:33.359
and updating my inventory as they went up and down.

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:36.720
And I was replenishing and orders were coming in.

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:39.320
And every day this report would run

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:44.320
and then send me an alert or not send an alert

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:47.399
based on whether the inventory level

00:07:47.399 --> 00:07:50.079
crossed a certain low-end threshold

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:52.279
that I wanted to trigger the action

00:07:52.279 --> 00:07:55.440
for taking more 3D printing on.

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:01.279
So this is my inventory control report.

00:08:01.279 --> 00:08:04.559
And what I can do in Connect,

00:08:04.559 --> 00:08:07.679
this is the publisher view within Connect.

00:08:07.679 --> 00:08:10.359
I can control the access settings to it.

00:08:10.359 --> 00:08:14.359
I can set just me to be able to see it,

00:08:14.359 --> 00:08:18.040
or I can open it up so that anyone can see it on the server.

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:19.880
I can add collaborators.

00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:22.000
So if I wanted to add Rachel,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.040
if she comes on board, I hire her as like,

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:27.399
hey, I'm gonna keep track of my inventory now.

00:08:27.399 --> 00:08:30.559
I should probably add you as a collaborator to this report.

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:34.039
So now she can come and manage this report,

00:08:34.039 --> 00:08:36.719
produce updates to it, check my code

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:38.359
and make sure it's correct.

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:44.159
And I can add a link so that we can share this report

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:45.559
with other folks.

00:08:45.559 --> 00:08:50.080
And we don't have to share this like ugly, long URL.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:54.640
We can make a cute, short URL, like a cookie report.

00:08:57.200 --> 00:08:58.119
Save that.

00:08:59.119 --> 00:09:02.000
And then we can distribute this whole thing

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.599
just based off of this individual link.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:09.320
That's the open solo view.

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:11.440
Back to the publisher view.

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:15.200
The other thing that's really useful here,

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:17.159
as I mentioned, is to have this report

00:09:17.159 --> 00:09:18.239
running on a schedule.

00:09:18.239 --> 00:09:22.119
So we want this to run, you know, daily, every day

00:09:23.039 --> 00:09:25.919
at maybe 6 a.m.

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:27.119
That'll be good.

00:09:27.119 --> 00:09:30.280
6 a.m., that'll be 9 a.m. for Rachel

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:33.520
since I'm on the West Coast, she's on the East Coast.

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:35.479
And we'll need to collaborate on this.

00:09:35.479 --> 00:09:39.440
And then I wanna send a custom email after the update,

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:43.239
but I don't want it to send every day.

00:09:43.239 --> 00:09:45.520
I only want it to send us an email

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:49.400
if the inventory falls below a certain level

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:51.159
for a certain color.

00:09:51.159 --> 00:09:55.159
So I've written that logic using a Plastula package

00:09:55.159 --> 00:09:58.799
into a custom email associated with this content item.

00:09:58.799 --> 00:10:02.640
We publish both the report and the email together

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:04.280
as a bundle here on Connect.

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:09.039
So now when I set this report up to get published

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:11.960
and run every day,

00:10:13.799 --> 00:10:15.000
this will send me the email.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.159
I have a little screenshot of it.

00:10:17.159 --> 00:10:18.599
I won't show you my actual email

00:10:18.599 --> 00:10:19.960
because that's a disaster.

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:23.599
But here's what a report email looks like.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:26.799
I have a little banner image and it lets us know

00:10:26.799 --> 00:10:29.359
that we need to go check the inventory levels

00:10:29.359 --> 00:10:31.400
and everything is wonderful.

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:36.400
So those are the basics of managing access,

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:41.239
distribution, scheduling for a report-type content item.

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:43.200
There are a couple of other things that you can do here

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:46.760
that not everybody takes advantage of on the Connect server.

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:48.359
One is tagging.

00:10:48.359 --> 00:10:52.400
If you want to go through and add a level of organization

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:54.200
to your Connect server,

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:57.679
you can have an admin set up a tag schema for you.

00:10:57.679 --> 00:11:00.559
And as a publisher, that means that you have access

00:11:00.559 --> 00:11:05.559
to all of the tags that your tag schema will provide.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:08.440
So these are hierarchical tags,

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:11.559
which means that they work a little interesting.

00:11:11.559 --> 00:11:14.440
If I want to tag something as Python content,

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:18.520
I can then go in and tag it as a subclass of Python content.

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:22.719
So I can apply the Python tag and save the dash tag.

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:25.559
Now, that doesn't make sense for this particular document

00:11:25.559 --> 00:11:27.000
since I wrote it in R,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:27.960
but that's just an example

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:30.640
of how the hierarchical tag system works.

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:33.280
So you'll see that I tagged this as email

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:36.359
since it has a custom email associated with it.

00:11:36.359 --> 00:11:38.359
And this is our sales demo server.

00:11:38.359 --> 00:11:40.559
You'll be able to find reports

00:11:40.559 --> 00:11:43.880
that have custom emails associated with them very quickly.

00:11:44.880 --> 00:11:49.880
So that's the basics of kind of how to manage

00:11:50.239 --> 00:11:53.880
a single content item on Connect.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:58.280
And I think this works like really well

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:00.880
for single items, at least.

00:12:00.880 --> 00:12:04.840
If you are in a scenario where today you have Connect

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:08.799
and you only have like five different content items

00:12:08.799 --> 00:12:10.479
and they're all beautiful,

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:13.440
you've set vanity URLs for them and they're all tagged,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.559
maybe you don't even need tags, you only have five items.

00:12:16.559 --> 00:12:18.239
So everything is labeled

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:20.400
and maybe your stakeholders have to do

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:21.880
a little bit of reading.

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:23.400
They've read the description,

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:28.400
associated metadata and thumbnail images with them.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:33.080
Everything is fairly discoverable.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:35.239
Content discovery is not an issue for you.

00:12:36.159 --> 00:12:37.599
But if you're like me,

00:12:37.599 --> 00:12:39.799
and I hope that a lot of you are

00:12:39.799 --> 00:12:42.640
because I find it really exciting

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:45.760
to build these content items and publish them.

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:50.599
If I start a project, it very quickly turns into like,

00:12:50.599 --> 00:12:53.760
I was trying to make a shiny application

00:12:53.760 --> 00:12:57.320
and all of a sudden now I have like three pins

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:01.200
and two static documents and a scheduled document

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:05.359
and like a graveyard of like old content items

00:13:05.359 --> 00:13:06.760
that were my prototypes.

00:13:06.760 --> 00:13:09.239
And I've got like an instrumentation dashboard

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:11.799
off to the side that's watching the usage

00:13:11.799 --> 00:13:13.559
of this shiny application.

00:13:13.559 --> 00:13:15.880
And this project just explodes.

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:20.119
And now you've got five or six content items

00:13:20.119 --> 00:13:23.159
that are all part of a single project.

00:13:23.159 --> 00:13:27.359
You don't have just one report

00:13:27.359 --> 00:13:30.559
that's the output of your data science work.

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:33.119
Now you've got this body of work

00:13:33.119 --> 00:13:35.719
that all needs to be tracked

00:13:35.719 --> 00:13:39.640
and understood as a cohesive unit.

00:13:40.520 --> 00:13:42.000
Sometimes that means like

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
you've got additional collaborators coming on board.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.119
There's all of this complexity that comes

00:13:47.119 --> 00:13:50.840
with building out data science artifacts.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:55.119
And as far as Connect is concerned,

00:13:55.119 --> 00:14:00.119
making something that adds a layer of content discovery

00:14:01.119 --> 00:14:05.440
at this sort of complex project level

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:09.119
has not been something we've yet taken on

00:14:09.119 --> 00:14:11.359
until hopefully now.

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:16.359
So I've not been the only one experiencing this issue.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:20.320
We have had lots of other customers reach out to us

00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:23.760
and I wanted to acknowledge those things we hear you

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:27.440
and really appreciate the feedback at this level.

00:14:27.559 --> 00:14:29.840
So this slide is all about

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:33.640
how much I appreciate hearing from our customers

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:36.400
and your feedback and listening

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:38.919
to what you'd like the product to do in the future.

00:14:38.919 --> 00:14:41.559
So please keep that coming.

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:44.080
What we've heard from customers is that

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:46.840
you're producing a lot of pieces of related content

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:49.280
and you wanna share that all with viewers

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.919
but you're not sure how to do that now

00:14:51.919 --> 00:14:55.280
given the tools that we've had in Connect historically.

00:14:55.599 --> 00:14:59.440
Giving your stakeholders pages and blanks is tiresome.

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:01.719
The default Connect content dashboard

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:04.679
isn't polished enough to share.

00:15:04.679 --> 00:15:07.880
You want to create sort of an app gallery

00:15:07.880 --> 00:15:11.520
or a content gallery app store

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:14.479
for your content items on Connect.

00:15:15.559 --> 00:15:17.840
You wanna have custom landing pages

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:21.280
for business stakeholders or different groups.

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:26.280
You want to make the content dashboard less overwhelming

00:15:26.359 --> 00:15:29.119
and content discovery easier.

00:15:30.119 --> 00:15:34.760
The final piece is a piece of feedback that we took

00:15:34.760 --> 00:15:38.520
and then changed during the design process.

00:15:38.520 --> 00:15:41.320
And I wanna give you a little peek behind the curtain

00:15:41.320 --> 00:15:44.960
at our design process and how we built out this feature set.

00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:47.799
So the final piece of feedback we got on this was

00:15:47.799 --> 00:15:49.200
it would be amazing if Connect

00:15:49.239 --> 00:15:52.440
could automatically generate a gallery.

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:55.440
And that was something we really did consider here

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:57.679
and we decided to move in a different direction.

00:15:57.679 --> 00:16:02.679
And I hope that this will still satisfy

00:16:03.719 --> 00:16:08.200
the core sentiment of this ask in what we built

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:11.919
but it's something that we could revisit over time.

00:16:11.919 --> 00:16:14.760
At our studio, we really cherish it

00:16:15.479 --> 00:16:20.479
and love to think of our users as folks who write code.

00:16:24.359 --> 00:16:28.080
It makes us very nervous to do things automatically

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:28.919
for you.

00:16:28.919 --> 00:16:30.640
There's lots of magic that exists

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:32.880
within the package ecosystem.

00:16:32.880 --> 00:16:36.719
But at the end of the day, by using the R package

00:16:36.719 --> 00:16:41.640
ecosystem, Python libraries, by writing things out in code

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:45.200
you're making those patterns reproducible for yourself

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:49.200
at least in theory that's more reproducible

00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:51.599
for yourself at least.

00:16:51.599 --> 00:16:55.080
So when we designed a solution to make content discovery

00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:58.479
a little bit easier to make these app stores

00:16:58.479 --> 00:17:02.640
or content galleries a reality in Connect,

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:07.640
we wanted to make that solution as self-service as possible

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:12.760
and rely on existing familiar Connect content types

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:17.040
rather than produce something that would magically

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:19.880
pull together your content items for you

00:17:19.880 --> 00:17:23.880
and make the end solution more rigid

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:26.800
and less reproducible that we wanted.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:29.079
So we wanted it to be code-based.

00:17:29.079 --> 00:17:31.199
We wanted it to, again, like I said,

00:17:31.199 --> 00:17:35.839
to be built upon familiar known Connect content types

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:38.160
like R Markdown and Shiny.

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:41.839
We wanted the end result to be still polished,

00:17:41.839 --> 00:17:44.599
have presentable defaults out of the box.

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:49.599
So not need or require you to do a lot of heavy-handed CSS

00:17:51.359 --> 00:17:54.680
or work on the design front to get something

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:55.880
that looks really great.

00:17:56.839 --> 00:18:00.400
We didn't want you to need to read the entire

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:03.920
Connect server API documentation book

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:05.599
in order to figure this out.

00:18:06.359 --> 00:18:07.719
We wanted to do some light hand-holding

00:18:07.719 --> 00:18:10.760
when it comes to working with our APIs

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:13.839
and we wanted it to be as customizable as possible

00:18:13.839 --> 00:18:17.359
and really easy to put your own branding on.

00:18:17.359 --> 00:18:20.560
So we produced an R package called Connect Widgets

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:23.400
that provides HTML widgets or helper functions

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:27.199
to organize and curate your RStudio Connect content

00:18:27.199 --> 00:18:30.959
within an R Markdown document or Shiny application.

